pr_description:
Fixes #1515 .

### Motivation
<!--
Does this solve a bug? Enable a new use-case? Improve an existing behavior? Concrete examples are helpful here.
-->
Using existing state to determine optimistic response is valuable in some cases to resolve race conditions

### Example - toggle

```ts
const toggle = new Endpoint(
  (): Promise<boolean> =>
    fetch(`/toggle/`, { method: 'POST' }).then(res => res.json()),
  {
    name: 'toggle',
    optimisticUpdater(snap) {
      const { data } = snap.getResponse(getbool);
      if (!data) throw new NoOptimistic();
      return data ? false : true;
    },
  },
);
```

### Example - PATCH

/updateVisSettings

```
{
  id: 5,
  visType: 'graph',
  numCols: 5,
  modifiedAt: {client:1642805150493, server: 1642805150493 }, // vector clock
}
```

```ts
class VisSettings extends Entity {
  pk() { return this.id; }

  static merge(existing, incoming) {
    if (existing.modifiedAt.client < incoming.modifiedAt.client
      || existing.modifiedAt.server< incoming.modifiedAt.server) {
       return {....existing, ...incoming}
    }
    return existing;
  }
}

const updateVisSettings= new Endpoint(
  (id, body) => fetch(`/updateVisSettings/${id}`, { method: 'PATCH', body: { ...body, modifiedAt: Date.now() }).then(res => res.json()),
  {
    optimisticUpdater(snap, id, body) {
      const { data } = snap.getResponse(getVisSettings, id);
      return { id, ...body, modifiedAt: {client: body.modifiedAt, server: data.modifiedAt.server } };
    },
    schema: VisSettings,
  }
);
```

```ts
getVisSettings(5);
/*
{
  id: 5,
  visType: 'graph',
  numCols: 5,
}
*/
updateVisSettings(5, { visType: 'chart' });
/*
{
  id: 5,
  visType: 'chart',
  numCols: 5,
}
*/
updateVisSettings(5, { numCols: 3 });
/*
{
  id: 5,
  visType: 'chart',
  numCols: 3,
}
*/
/*
without using previous state it would instead be incorrectly
{
  id: 5,
  visType: 'graph',
  numCols: 3,
}
*/
```

### Solution
<!--
What is the solution here from a high level. What are the key technical decisions and why were they made?
-->

### Store

For operations during reducer, access to dispatch is banned. Thus we instantiate with current state building `Snapshot` from Controller and State

```ts
class Snapshot {
  private state: State;
  private controller: Controller;
  /*************** Data Access ***************/
  getResponse(endpoint, ...args)​ => { data, expiryStatus, expiresAt };
  getError(endpoint, ...args)​ => ErrorTypes | undefined;
  fetchStart: number;
}
```

### Endpoint.optimisticUpdater

`optimisticUpdate` supplemented by `optimisticUpdater` - the former to be deprecated.

```ts
export interface EndpointExtraOptions<F extends FetchFunction = FetchFunction> {
  /** Enables optimistic updates for this request - uses return value as assumed network response
  * to be deprecated
  */
  readonly optimisticUpdate?: (...args: Parameters<F>) => ResolveType<F>;

  /** Enables optimistic updates for this request - uses return value as assumed network response */
  readonly optimisticUpdater?: (snap: Snapshot, ...args: Parameters<F>) => ResolveType<F>;
}
```

This runs during reducer instead of action dispatcher.

### reducer -> createReducer

- close reducer around controller

```ts
case FETCH_TYPE: {
  let optimisticResponse = action.meta.optimisticResponse;
  if (action.endpoint.optimisticUpdater) {
    optimisticResponse = action.meta.optimisticUpdater.call(action.endpoint, controller.snapshot(state), ...action.meta.args);
  }
}
```

- test lib has a check to determine which to use
- will continue exporting reducer closed around a global controller to keep compatibility. people using this method should not have issues as they won't rely on that controller. however, it is best to take control of the lifetime of the global cache, and thus it is not recommended for use otherwise. will mark it deprecated.

### OptimisticAction

Since optimistic actions compute their payload on receiving, we don't send a payload, therefore we want a new action to reflect that. This also triggers codepath to use endpoints' optimicUpdater function.

### filterOptimistic() changes

Previously optimistic actions would be filtered if they occurred before a response. This was done to prevent optimistic responses queued up from overriding fetches that are resolved after.

While this solves one specific race condition, it does not allow for handling others. The first is that it only handles one race condition; but does not allow for handling cases like toggles or if earlier fetches take longer to even reach the server.

#### Now

For `optimisticUpdater` triggered updates, fetch resolution will only remove its corresponding optimistic action.

The previously handled race condition can be done more robustly as well every other case, by using Entity.merge logic instead.

For example, even without changing an actual server API, artificially adding the time stamp of fetch initiation allows replicating previous behavior:

```ts
class OpEntity extends Entity {
  
  static merge(existing, incoming, existingMeta, incomingMeta) {
    if (existingMeta.date<= incomingMeta.date) {
      return {...existing, ...incoming};
    }
    return existing;
  }
}

const updateOptimistically = new Endpoint(
  async (id, body) => fetch(`/updateVisSettings/${id}`, { method: 'PATCH', body ).then(res => res.json()),
  {
    optimisticUpdater(snap, id, body) {
      const { data } = snap.getResponse(getVisSettings, id);
      return { id, ...data, ...body };
    },
    schema: OpEntity ,
  }
);
```

### Deprecation summary

- reducer -> createReducer
- Endpoint.optimisticUpdate -> Endpoint.optimisticUpdater
- Entity.merge(existing, incoming) -> Entity.merge(existing, incoming, existingMeta, incomingMeta)

### Review notes

- I highly recommend hiding whitespace when viewing diff
- packages/core/src/react-integration/__tests__/integration-optimistic-legacy-endpoint.web.tsx: this is copy/paste of existing tests (packages/core/src/react-integration/tests/integration-optimistic-endpoint.web.tsx). to validate existing endpoints. The above file is then adapted for new methods

### Future work

Incorporate snapshot concept into all side effect methods like 'update'

