pr_description:
## Motivation
<!--
Does this solve a bug? Enable a new use-case? Improve an existing behavior? Concrete examples are helpful here.
-->
[Previously](https://github.com/data-client/rest-hooks/pull/403), we introduced the global referential equality invariant, enabling efficient memoization with all user-land usage of rest-hooks. However, the initial implementation required still running the whole denormalization algorithm even when the result ended up being the same and simply only retrieved from cache. This meant that while user-code performance and reliability would improve, the actual rest-hooks path ended up being more expensive.

Reads are by far the most common operation - especially considering the general nature of react design where you often re-compute the same components. Therefore, speedups to this operation can have a potentially very large impact.

Here we propose a full short-circuit path for denormalization based on cached values - not only making the responses globally consistent, but also enabling full memoization benefits of computation avoidance.

## Solution
<!--
What is the solution here from a high level. What are the key technical decisions and why were they made?
-->

> Because cache is no longer proportional to the complexity of the operation, the retrieval cost is close to fixed - resulting in
> denormalizeLong performance increase of 2380%

<details open>

| Benchmark suite | Current: 8f7883cc5c4fa9818e225290c3d937590ab0204c | Previous: 28f3fe8890da119c7fa6498d4617a66da74ed0b4 | Ratio |
|-|-|-|-|
| `normalizeLong` | `318` ops/sec (`±2.02%`) | `340` ops/sec (`±0.49%`) | `1.07` |
| `infer All` | `7157` ops/sec (`±0.41%`) | `7056` ops/sec (`±0.35%`) | `0.99` |
| `denormalizeLong` | `160` ops/sec (`±1.86%`) | `209` ops/sec (`±1.46%`) | `1.31` |
| `denormalizeLong withCache` | `5078` ops/sec (`±0.11%`) | `252` ops/sec (`±0.16%`) | `0.049625836943678614` |
| `denormalizeLong All withCache` | `5947` ops/sec (`±0.27%`) | `251` ops/sec (`±0.19%`) | `0.04220615436354464` |
| `denormalizeLong Query-sorted withCache` | `5832` ops/sec (`±0.21%`) | `245` ops/sec (`±0.20%`) | `0.04200960219478738` |
| `getResponse` | `5047` ops/sec (`±2.90%`) | `249` ops/sec (`±0.28%`) | `0.049336239350108974` |
| `getSmallResponse` | `1890` ops/sec (`±0.14%`) | `641` ops/sec (`±0.10%`) | `0.34` |
| `setLong` | `315` ops/sec (`±2.65%`) | `338` ops/sec (`±0.28%`) | `1.07` |
| `setLongWithMerge` | `129` ops/sec (`±0.35%`) | `129` ops/sec (`±0.27%`) | `1` |
| `setLongWithSimpleMerge` | `137` ops/sec (`±0.26%`) | `136` ops/sec (`±0.22%`) | `0.99` |

</details>

### Currently

We recompute denormalize every time because we need to build the deps list to lookup in globalCacheEntry. This is still better than a new one, but the traversal is most of the cost so it doesn’t save much.

### New idea

To avoid this, we can additionally cache the lookup paths to these to enable us to compare its latest value with the previous to see if it has changed. This way we can completely short-circuit all denormalization if all deps have not changed. Similarly, we only need to denormalize parts where any of its member change. So for instance, if a top level entity changes, but other cousins do not - the entire cousin tree can be pulled from cache and quickly combined with the new top level entity for a final result.

#### The example case

```tsx
class User extends IDEntity {}
class Comment extends IDEntity {
  comment = '';
  static schema = {
    user: User,
  };
}
class Article extends IDEntity {
  title = '';
  body = '';
  static schema = {
    author: User,
    comments: [Comment],
  };
}
```

```
{
Article:5:{article},
User: 100:{user100},200:{user200},
Comment: 1:{comment1-user200},2:{comment2 -user100},3:{comment3-user200}
}
```

#### One step, many parts

This has redundant path entries, but we only traverse once. Presumably traversing and array deps building are the expensive parts.

We can still track cycles by stopping with any seen elements

Set still requires us to traverse and track full deps. however, retrieval does not

multi-schema: we can do the first lookup based on the entity schema itself, because if any pieces were different they would make the outer most different.

```tsx
key->pk->WM(entitySchema -> WEM(article5 -> path+user100 -> path+comment1 -> path+user200 -> path+comment2 -> path+comment3 -> value))

set([{entity: article5, path: {article,5}}, {

entity=comment3
path={comment,3}
```

```tsx
// results cache
WM(results -> WEM(deps -> [value, bool, bool]))
```

#### WeakEntityMap

```ts
class WeakEntityMap<K extends object, V> {
    readonly next: WeakMap<K, Link<K, V>>;
    get(entity: K, state: State<K>): V | undefined;
    set(dependencies: Dep<K>[], value: V): void;
    /** Builds essentially the same intereface but binds entity state */
    static fromState<K extends object, V, T extends WeakEntityMap<K, V>>(wem: T, state: State<K>): {
        get(entity: K): V | undefined;
        set(deps: Dep<K>[], value: V): void;
    };
}
/** Link in a chain */
declare class Link<K extends object, V> {
    next: WeakMap<K, Link<K, V>>;
    value?: V;
    nextPath?: Path;
}
export interface Path {
    key: string;
    pk: string;
}
export interface Dep<K = object> {
    path: Path;
    entity: K;
}
```

#### Complications

- cycles
  - existing solution should continue as our deps list has simply expanded in what is contained (see `Dep` above)
- multi-schema entities ([Summary List Endpoints](https://resthooks.io/rest/guides/summary-list))
  - since we skip running denormalization, having differences in the schema (Entity) definition itself would potentially result in different outcomes. Because of this we add another WeakMap in front of the global entity cache keyed on the Entity definition itself.
  - This means to ensure referential equality (and computational savings) one should not send dynamically computed Entities
  - *TL;DR) all cached are keyed on schema*

## Alternatives considered

#### 2 step

We could simply introduce another cache to find the path values. Once taken, the full dependency list could be built, allowing indexing into the WeakListMap.

This would be a very straightforward change, but result in WM tree traversal twice, which is likely to be ill performant. Furthermore, the WEM data structure turned out to be quite small code, making it as a full replacement quite reasonable.

```ts
step 1: get deps - we know when to stop by tracking what we've visited.
to support multi-schema, we would need to also index on schema here (article5+schema ->)
key->pk->WM(
	article5->[{user,100},{comment,1},{comment,2},{comment,3}],
	user100->[],
	user200->[],
	comment1->[{user,200}],
	comment2->[{user,100}],
	comment3->[{user,200}],
)
step 2: lookup (already here)
key->pk->WM(
	article5->user100 -> comment1 -> user200 -> comment2 -> comment3 -> value,
	user100->value,
	user200->value,
	comment1->user200->value
	comment2->user100->value
	comment3->user200->value
)
```

## Future work

This did result in a measurable performance slowdown (30%) for the first denormalization call, so it would be good to look to optimize the book-keeping with this base implementation.

- Still some explorations to be done about dependency tracking as bookkeeper there seems to still hold decent overhead.
- Cache inferResults to ensure schema.All can be memoized

