### Motivation
<!--
Does this solve a bug? Enable a new use-case? Improve an existing behavior? Concrete examples are helpful here.
-->

Memoizing queries at a global level makes them much more useful.

### Solution
<!--
What is the solution here from a high level. What are the key technical decisions and why were they made?
-->

#### MemoCache

We introduce to normalizr: MemoCache. This reduces the implementation boundaries exposed to a simple class that has two methods, query and denormalize. This way the details like WeakEntityMap, etc are not exposed.

This also has the advantage of removing the awkward cache object parameters to an already long parameter list.

```ts
const memo = new MemoCache();
const data = memo.query(key, schema, args, state.entities, state.indexes);
const { data, paths } = memo.denormalize(input, schema, state.entities, args);
const queryKey = memo.buildQueryKey(
  key,
  schema,
  args,
  state.entities,
  state.indexes,
);
```

The advantages in its usage are easily seen by the massive simplification of the test suite that relies on this.

#### queryKey

```ts
class Entity {
  static queryKey(
    args: any[],
    queryKey: (
      schema: any,
      args: any,
      getEntity: GetEntity,
      getIndex: GetIndex,
    ) => any,
    getEntity: GetEntity,
    getIndex: GetIndex,
  ): any {
      if (!args[0]) return;
      const id = queryKeyCandidate(this, args, getIndex);
      // ensure this actually has entity or we shouldn't try to use it in our query
      if (getEntity(this.key, id)) return id;
    }
}
```

